##Frequency Table for Hours Worked and Performance Score - ChatGPT

#ChatGPT used to create this visualization
# Sample data: Replace this with your actual dataset
set.seed(123)
work_table <- data.frame(
  Work_Hours_Per_Week = sample(30:60, 100, replace = TRUE),
  Performance_Score = sample(1:5, 100, replace = TRUE)
)

# Define bins for Work_Hours_Per_Week
breaks <- seq(30, 60, by = 5)

# Create non-overlapping bins for Work_Hours_Per_Week
work_table$Work_Hours_Bins <- cut(work_table$Work_Hours_Per_Week, breaks = breaks, include.lowest = TRUE, right = FALSE)

# Create a contingency table for Work_Hours_Bins and Performance_Score
contingency_table <- table(work_table$Work_Hours_Bins, work_table$Performance_Score)

# Convert the contingency table to a data frame
contingency_table_df <- as.data.frame(contingency_table)
colnames(contingency_table_df) <- c("Work_Hours_Bins", "Performance_Score", "Frequency")

# Calculate the total number of observations in the dataset
total_observations <- sum(contingency_table_df$Frequency)

# Calculate overall percentages for each combination
contingency_table_df$Percentage <- (contingency_table_df$Frequency / total_observations) * 100

# Display the resulting data frame
print(contingency_table_df)

##Heatmap of Frequency Table
#ChatGTP used to create this visualization
#Looking to find if "Performance_Scores" decrease as "Work Hours per Week" increases
heatmap_plot <- ggplot(contingency_table_df, aes(x = Work_Hours_Bins, y = Performance_Score, fill = Percentage)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "navy", high = "red", name = "Percentage") +
  labs(
    title = "Heatmap of Work Hours and Performance Scores",
    x = "Work Hours Bins",
    y = "Performance Score"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 10),
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 14, face = "bold")
  )

# Display the heatmap
print(heatmap_plot)

Note: What we are looking for here is red in either the top left or bottom right. Why? If Red is in the top left corner it would support the hypothesis less hours worked, greater performance. If Red is in the bottom right corner it would also support the hypothesis because more hours worked equates to worse performance. From this heatmap, the sweet spot looks like 35-40 hour work weeks. Could a 35 hour workweek be better than 40? Half days on Friday?

Note/Analysis: The table & dataframe looks into the frequency distribution for each performance score level and each Work Hours Per Week. Having said that, when focusing on only the 5-Rating Performance Score level, the standard deviation of the frequency is 27.91. In other words, the number of employees with a Performance score of 5 does not significantly change as Work_Hours_Per_Week increases. The most 5-Rating Performance Score levels comes from working 40 hours per week.

When focusing on only the 1-Rating Performance Score level, the standard deviation of the frequency is 30.26. In other words, the number of employees with a Performance score of 1 does not significantly change as Work_Hours_Per_Week increases. An interesting insight, the most 1-rating performance scores came from working 58 hours per week. The least 1-rating performance scores came from working 43 hours per week.

Overall, the number of hours worked per week does not seem to heavily influence performance scores.

Note/Analysis: Monthly Salary and Job_Title appear to be the most important in predicting Performance Score. Logically that checks out. The more an employee is being paid, performance should increase. As for Job_Title, this makes sense also. People with a lower job, for example working at Chick-Fil-A as a server, likely do not input the same effort and energy relative to that of a CEO at Apple.

Sick Days and Employee Satisfaction Score do appear to have some impact on Performance_Score. Specifically, as Sick Days and Employee Satisfaction Score increases, Performance_Score increases. However, this is not extremely significant.

Because Monthly_Salary and Job_Title were so significant in the model, a model was built excluding them (rf_adjust). With this model, other variables such as Employee_Satisfaction_Score appear to be more important in predicting Performance_Score. Having said that, when looking at the Partial Plots the changes are little (Changes in tenths, hundreths).

##XgBoost Model

#Set seed to get same output for sequence of numbers
set.seed(7)

#Split the data into test and training sets
portion <- createDataPartition(work$Performance_Score, p = 0.70, list = F)
train_work <- work[portion, ]
test_work <- work[-portion, ]

#define predictor and response variables in training set
train_x = data.matrix(train_work[, -9])
train_y = train_work[,9]

#define predictor and response variables in testing set
test_x = data.matrix(test_work[, -9])
test_y = test_work[, 9]

#define final training and testing sets
xgb_train = xgb.DMatrix(data = train_x, label = train_y)
xgb_test = xgb.DMatrix(data = test_x, label = test_y)

#define watchlist
watchlist = list(train=xgb_train, test=xgb_test)

#fit XGBoost model and display training and testing data at each round
model = xgb.train(data = xgb_train, max.depth = 3, watchlist=watchlist, nrounds = 200)

Note/Analysis: Correlation does not equal causation. The XgBoost model reflects that Job Title and Performance Score contribute the most to Monthly Salary. Having said that, it is difficult, if not impossible to label which factor motivates the other. People with a better job title naturally have a better salary. One could argue, to get a better salary, get a better job title. But the argument, work harder to get a better job title, to get a better salary, could be made also. The boxplot reflects that naturally certain job titles will earn a better salary.
